04757nam a22006495i 9781442657106DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181997onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426571067 a10.3138/97814426571062doi  a(DE-B1597)497143  a(OCoLC)1076450408  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a971.0642201 aOwram, Doug, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBorn at the Right Time :bA History of the Baby Boom Generation /cDoug Owram. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Home and Family at Mid-Century -- t2. Babies -- t3. Safe in the Hands of Mother Suburbia: Home and Community, 1950-1965 -- t4. Consuming Leisure: Play in an Era of Affluence, 1950-1965 -- t5. School Days, 1952-1965 -- t6. The Fifties and the Cult of the Teenager -- t7. The Arrival of the Sixties -- t8. 'Hope I Die Before I Get Old': The Rise of the Counter-Culture, 1963-1968 -- t9 .Youth Radicalism in the Sixties -- t10. Sexual Revolutions and Revolutions of the Sexes, 1965-1973 -- t11. The End of the Sixties, 1968-1973 -- tEpilogue: A World without Limits -- tNotes -- tCredits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is rare in history for people to link their identity with their generation, and even rarer when children and adolescents actually shape society and influence politics. Both phenomena aptly describe the generation born in the decade following the Second World War. These were the baby boomers, viewed by some as the spoiled, selfish generation that had it all, and by others as a shock wave that made love and peace into tangible ideals. In this book, Doug Owram brings us the untold story of this famous generation as it played out its first twenty-five years in Canadian society. Beginning with Dr Spock's dictate that this particular crop of babies must be treated gently, Owram explores the myth and history surrounding this group, from its beginning at war's end to the close of the 1960s. The baby boomers wielded extraordinary power right from birth, Owram points out, and laid their claim on history while still in diapers. He sees the generation's power and sense of self stemming from three factors: its size, its affluent circumstance, and its connection with the 1960s – the fabulous decade of free love, flower power, women's liberation, drugs, protest marches, and rock 'n' roll. From Davy Crockett hats and Barbie dolls to the civil-rights movement and the sexual revolution, the concerns of this single generation became predominant themes for all of society. Thus, Owram's history of the baby-boomers is in many ways a history of the era. Doug Owram has written extensively on cultural icons, Utopian hopes, and the gap between realities and images – all powerful themes in the story of this idealistic generation. A well-researched, lucid, and humorous book, Born at the Right Time is the first Canadian history of the baby-boomers and the society they helped to shape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBaby boom generationzCanada. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144265710640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442657106423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442657106.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL 